body.p:
For XML, you must add CSS rules that pick up the content of an attribute
      and use it as a source for the
      video:...
<para>Like shown in this video: <video src="files/earth.mp4"/>.</para>
...For example, the CSS rules may look like
        this:video {
  display: inline;
}
video[src] {
  content: attr(src, url);
}It is important to use the url
        keyword when retrieving the attribute value. It signals that the value is a pointer to an
        external image.

section.p:
If your XML contains additional attributes such as width or
          height, you can complete the
          CSS:video[width] {
  width: attr(width, length);
}
video[height] {
  height: attr(height, length);
}


It is also possible to set both width and height
              attributes directly on the video object.

If no values are set for width/height (neither from the CSS nor attributes), the
              extracted video size will be used.

It is possible to change this placeholder with a custom one by using the -oxy-video-cover
        property:video {
  -oxy-video-cover: url("files/cover.png");
}
